<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1436,152,1186]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,310,786,812]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is characterised by the aedeagus that has the preatrium spinose, the shaft with the apex that is long, narrow and spine-like, the mediodorsal gonopore, and the shape of the female sternite 7. Possibly only two other species show some form of modification to the aedeagus. These are 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stiller" authorityYear="2010" box="[1250,1436,861,886]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pravistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caenophallus">
<emphasis box="[1250,1436,861,886]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">P. caenophallus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stiller" authorityYear="2010" box="[201,408,898,923]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pravistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="odontiophallus">
<emphasis box="[201,408,898,923]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">P. odontiophallus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stiller" authorityYear="2010" box="[456,663,898,923]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pravistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="odontiophallus">
<emphasis box="[456,663,898,923]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">P. odontiophallus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the apex of the shaft is sometimes expanded laterally but always with one or the other side bearing small teeth (
<figureCitation box="[728,881,936,962]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="64.[151,255,1673,1697]" captionTargetBox="[188,1400,199,1606]" captionTargetId="figure-144@64.[181,1405,194,1694]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 4 a–q. Pravistylus species. Aedeagus, dorsally or ventrally. a, P. lobus sp. n., dorsal; b, P. lobus sp. n., ventral; c, P. deltoplacus sp. n., dorsal; d, P. mecophysis sp. n., dorsal; e, P. bidentidiscus sp. n., dorsal; f, P. brachyplacus sp. n., dorsal; g, P. mollidiscus sp. n., dorsal; h, P. mecistoplacus sp. n., dorsal; i, P. mutilidiscus sp. n., dorsal; j, P. brachyphysis sp. n., ventral; k–l, P. odontiophallus sp. n., dorsal; m–n, P. eductus (Naudé), dorsal; o, P. exquadratus (Naudé), dorsal; p, P. tanyoplacus sp. n., dorsal; q, P. macropygeus sp. n., dorsal." pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Figs 4 k &amp; l</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stiller" authorityYear="2010" box="[941,1134,936,961]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pravistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caenophallus">
<emphasis box="[941,1134,936,961]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">P. caenophallus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the aedeagal shaft has a medial, dorsal keeled bilobate structure, and the apex is expanded laterad (
<figureCitation box="[1088,1167,973,999]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="62.[151,255,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[249,1353,187,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-126@62.[233,1361,182,1903]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURE 3 a–t. Pravistylus species. Aedeagus, laterally. a–b, P.lobus sp. n.; c, P. deltoplacussp. n.; d, P. mecophysis sp. n.; e, P. bidentidiscus sp. n.; f, P. brachyplacus sp. n.; g, P. mollidiscus sp. n.; h, P. mecistoplacus sp. n.; i–k, P. mutilidiscus sp. n.; l, P. brachyphysis sp. n.; m, P. odontiophallus sp. n.; n–o, P.eductus (Naudé); p–q, P. exquadratus (Naudé); r, P. tanyoplacus sp. n.; s, P. macropygeus sp. n.; t, P. pollediscus sp. n." pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Figs 3</figureCitation>
ak, 4 ai). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stiller" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pravistylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bidentidiscus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Pravistylus bidentidiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a similar structure of the plate (
<figureCitation box="[748,820,1010,1036]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="57.[151,255,1711,1735]" captionTargetBox="[198,1389,205,1619]" captionTargetId="figure-63@57.[190,1396,194,1718]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURE 2 a–i. Pravistylus species. Plate, part or whole structure. a, P. varicudiscus sp. n.; b, P. mecistoplacus sp. n.; c, P. digitidiscus sp. n.; d, P. tanyoplacus sp. n.; e–g, P.eductus(Naudé); h–i, P. exquadratus (Naudé)." pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
ar). In this species the medial apical margin of the plate is concave, with apical and medial teeth, with the style apophysis protruding beyond its margin. All the other species have the lateral or posterior margin of the plate modified or produced or acute, or narrowly or broadly rounded. Species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Theron" authorityName="Theron" authorityYear="1980" box="[485,726,1122,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Platentomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[485,631,1123,1148]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Platentomus</emphasis>
Theron
</taxonomicName>
, are characterised by the bilobate medial margin of the plate, but have the aedeagus with the apex of the shaft modified.
</paragraph>
